result.execSummary:
The defendant Aaron Scott Morris was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Expungement granted under 973.015 upon successful completion of sentence.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Aaron Scott Morris in court with attorney Rick Terrence Cveykus.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 5:35 PM. Also called 15CM204 - plead to count #1 as alleged, #2 and #3 to be DRI, #1 - $300.00 fine plus costs and surcharges, 15CM204 - DRI counts #1 and #3, plead NC to counts #2 and #4 as alleged, #2 - $300 fine plus court costs and surcharges, #4 - withhold sentence and place on probation for 1 year with conditions of : AODA and follow thru, maintain absolute sobreity, no possession of alcohol and no entry into any bars, taverns, liquor stores or similar establishments, 100 hours community service, employment/school. State and Morris agree. Court - 15CM226 - dismisses and reads in counts #2 and #3, 15CM204 - court dismisses and reads in counts #1 and #3. 15CM226 - Morris pleads G to count #1 as alleged. 15CM204 - defendant pleads G to counts #2 and #4. Court has plea questionnaire, goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his constitutional rights by entering his plea and right to JT, accepts plea, adjudges guilty, proceed to sentencing. State makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation. Cveykus makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation - asks for expunction. Morris makes statement. Court sentences the defendant to the following: 15CM226 - $300 fine plus costs and surcharges - take bond posted - remainder due in 30 days/CO; 15CM204 - count #2 - $300 fine plus costs and surcharges - take bond posted - remainder due in 30 days/CO, count #4 - withhold sentence and place on probation for 1 year with conditions of: AODA and follow thru, no possession or consumption of alcohol and no entry into any bars or taverns, 100 hours community service, attend at least one AA/NA or similar type program each week and provide verification of attendance to P&P, maintain/obtain full time employment/school, costs - to be paid in 30 days/CO, submit DNA sample on each case with surcharge assessed and expunction rights given, expungement allowed under 973.015 upon successful completion of probation and expunges 15CM226 upon successful completion of sentence, right to appeal, adjourned.
Plea/sentencing hearing on May 23, 2016 at 02:15 pm.
Jury trial on May 26, 2016 at 08:30 am.

Defendant Aaron Scott Morris in court with attorney Rick Terrence Cveykus.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Called at 9:10 AM. State - not resolved - set for JT. Cveykus and Morris agree - has gone over Frye with the defendant - client admitted self into inpatient treatment. Court instructs defendant that the offer will no longer exist after today. State - offer - 15CM226 - plead to counts #1 and #3 as alleged, 18 months probation on each count with conditions of: count #1 - 15 days jail and costs on #1 and $300 fine plus costs on #3, #2 - DRI. 15CM204 - plead to counts #2 and #4 as alleged, #2 - 60 days jail, $300 fine plus costs, #1 and #3 - DRI, #4 - 12 months probation with costs only with other standard conditions of probation. Cveykus makes statement, willing to set for sentencing and free to argue the jail sentence. Court responds. Court continues bond on both cases and both cases sets for JT.  Jury trial scheduled for May 26, 2016 at 08:30 am.
